<h3 id="example-2-an-advanced-formula">Example 2: An advanced formula</h3>
<p>For this example, the cost of electricity should not just follow the actual electricity that is consumed in kWh. Management wants to incorporate incentive for lowering electricity usage.</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Rule</th>
<th>Rate</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>a &lt;= 10000,00 kWh</td>
<td>0.75</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>a &gt; 10000,00 kWh</td>
<td>1.15</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>A new formula allocation base, Electricity usage, is created.</p>
<p><strong>Formula allocation base</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Cost element dimension</th>
<th>Statistical dimension</th>
<th>Formula</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Electricity usage</td>
<td></td>
<td>Statistical elements</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Before the <strong>Formula</strong> field can be filled, you must specify the alias that should be used in the formula.</p>
<p><strong>Formula allocation base factors</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Alias</th>
<th>Constant</th>
<th>Allocation base</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>a</td>
<td></td>
<td>Electricity</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>b</td>
<td>10,000.00</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>c</td>
<td>0.75</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>d</td>
<td>1.15</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Formula allocation base</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Cost element dimension</th>
<th>Statistical dimension</th>
<th>Formula</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Electricity fixed</td>
<td></td>
<td>Statistical elements</td>
<td>((a &gt; b) × ((b × c) + (a – b) × d)) + ((a &lt;= b] × a × c)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>A Preview function lets you validate the formula allocation base that is created, based on statistical entries in the system.</p>
<p><strong>Allocation base details</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Cost object</th>
<th></th>
<th>Formula</th>
<th>Magnitude</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CC001</td>
<td>HR</td>
<td>((2,450.00 &gt; 10.000.00) × ((10,000.00 × 0.75) + (2,450.00 – 10,000.00) × 1.15)) + ((2,450.00 &lt;= 10,000.00) × 2,450.00 × 0.75)</td>
<td>1,837.50</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CC002</td>
<td>FI</td>
<td>((4,100.00 &gt; 10.000.00) × ((10,000.00 × 0.75) + (4,100.00 – 10,000.00) × 1.15)) + ((4,100.00 &lt;= 10,000.00) × 4,100.00 × 0.75)</td>
<td>3,075.00</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CC003</td>
<td>IT</td>
<td>((15,000.00 &gt; 10.000.00) × ((10,000.00 × 0.75) + (15,000.00 – 10,000.00) × 1.15)) + ((15,000.00 &lt;= 10,000.00) × 15,000.00 × 0.75)</td>
<td>1,3250.00</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Here is a closer look at the formula for CC003 (IT):</p>
<p>((15,000.00 &gt; 10,000.00) × ((10,000.00 × 0.75) + (15,000.00 – 10,000.00) × 1.15)) + ((15,000.00 &lt;= 10,000.00) × 15,000.00 × 0.75) = 13,250.00</p>
